{
  "text": "To prove this, they consider a specific infinite set Y \u2286 \u03c9 and then show that it is \u03a3 1 1 -definable in (M, X). However, their purported \u03a0 1 1 -definition of Y does not work as it actually defines the set Y \u222a (M\\\u03c9). Smory\u0144ski makes a similar error in his explicit claim [CITATION_1] Lemma 4.2] that if M is nonstandard and not recursively saturated and (M, X) |= ACA 0 , then \u03c9 is \u2206 1 1 -definable in (M, X). We will show in Theorem 2 that this approach is doomed since there are nonstandard models M that are not recursively saturated even though \u03c9 is 1 All usages of definable in this paper should be understood as definable with parameters.",
